    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait lol what? what do goblins have to do with my muscles? i was just asking about the science of it. can u just explain the actual chemical process without the weird analogies?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the confusion. Let's dive straight into the science of it. When you engage in high-intensity activities like sprinting, your muscles require energy at a rate that exceeds the oxygen supply available to them. To meet this demand, your muscles switch to anaerobic metabolism, which doesn't require oxygen but produces lactic acid as a byproduct.\n\nLactic acid is formed when pyruvate, a product of glycolysis (the breakdown of glucose for energy), is reduced by the enzyme lactate dehydrogenase. This process occurs when the oxygen supply is insufficient to meet the energy demands of your muscles, leading to the accumulation of lactic acid in the muscles and bloodstream.\n\nThe presence of lactic acid in the muscles can cause the sensation of burning and fatigue, which is why you might feel your legs \"on fire\" during intense exercise. Over time, the body works to clear the lactic acid. It can be converted back into pyruvate and then used in the mitochondria for aerobic respiration, which produces more energy and doesn't produce lactic acid. Alternatively, lactic acid can be transported to the liver, where it is converted back into glucose through a process called gluconeogenesis.\n\nThis process of clearing lactic acid and",
